## Learnings & Patterns

*Captured insights about BeFirst Platform development patterns and architecture decisions.*

### Report Organization (Portal)

**Pattern:** `Index` as landing page + specific report actions (2026-05-12)

**Structure:**
```
Areas/{AreaName}/Controllers/ReportsController.cs
  ├── Index()              → Landing page listing all reports
  ├── {ReportName}()       → Specific report (e.g., UserMemberships)
  └── Get{Data}()          → AJAX partials for report sections

Areas/{AreaName}/Views/Reports/
  ├── Index.cshtml         → Report cards/links
  ├── {ReportName}.cshtml  → Full report page
  └── _{Partial}.cshtml    → Reusable sections
```

**Key Characteristics:**
- **Landing Page:** `Index.cshtml` displays cards with report descriptions and links
- **Specific Actions:** Each report gets its own action (e.g., `UserMemberships()`, `BonusHistory()`)
- **Scalability:** Easy to add new reports without breaking existing ones
- **Authorization:** Controller-level `[Authorize(Roles = "...")]` for area-wide access
- **Partials:** AJAX-loaded partials for performance (load on-demand)
- **Print Styling:** `@@media print` with CSP nonce for compliance documentation

**Location Examples:**
- `Manage/Reports/UserMemberships` - User role/position audit
- `Personnel/Reports/BonusHistory` - Employee bonus tracking

**Technical Patterns:**
- Use `Firstronic.Framework.Queries.GetDatatableFromQuery()` for raw SQL
- DataTable → View model for reporting queries
- `<script nonce="@Html.ScriptNonce()">` inline (no `@section scripts`)
- Layout `_Layout_portal.cshtml` supports: `head`, `Footer`, `FooterBottom` sections only

**Why This Pattern:**
- Multiple reports per area without URL conflicts
- Clear navigation hierarchy for users
- Maintainable structure for developers
- Follows existing Personnel/Reports pattern
